<p>
<seg id=1> The Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean (ECLAC) predicted that, the economic growth of that region will drop to 1% next year. </seg>
<seg id=2> However, this organization admitted that the situation could have been worse. </seg>
<seg id=3> Please listen to the detailed report by Michael from the Southern America Department of the Voice of America, announced by Yie Tian. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The UN Economic Commission observed that, the rate of economic growth in Latin America and the Caribbean region will be 2.3% this year, which dropped sharply when compared to the rate of 5.2% last year. </seg>
<seg id=5> This year's rate could have been even lower if the economy did not run strongly in the first half year. </seg>
<seg id=6> This Commission said that, despite the turbulent situation outside of the region, regional economics appeared comparatively well. </seg>
<seg id=7> However, the worst affects have appeared and will last until next year. </seg>
<seg id=8> The UN Economic Commission said that, the difficult economic situation in Brazil was also reflected in some other southern countries located in the triangle region. </seg>
<seg id=9> These countries suffered most from the low prices of their export products. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Commission said that, most of these countries opted for high interests to protect their currencies. </seg>
<seg id=11> This measure restrained the economies growth, and caused the unemployment rate to increase. </seg>
<seg id=12> The report said that these countries will have to face the risk of high inflation if they want to retain their competitiveness in the global market. </seg>
</p>
